04530nam a22006975i 9780292799394DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20211995txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927993947 a10.7560/7309912doi  a(DE-B1597)588149  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aF1465.2.C3bH46 1995eb 7aSOC0000002bisacsh04a391/.0089/9742201 aHendrickson, Carol, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWeaving Identities :bConstruction of Dress and Self in a Highland Guatemala Town /cCarol Hendrickson. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©1995  a1 online resource (261 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tList of Tables -- tList of Figures -- tList of Photographs -- tAcknowledgments -- tNote on Kaqchikel Orthography -- t1. Introduction -- t2. The Geography of Clothing -- t3. The Enduring Indian: Images of the Maya -- t4. Between Birth and Death: -- t5. The Cultural Biography of Traje -- t6. Transforming the Traditional: -- t7. To Wear Traje Is to Say "We Are Maya" -- tNotes -- tGlossary -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aTraje, the brightly colored traditional dress of the highland Maya, is the principal visual expression of indigenous identity in Guatemala today. Whether worn in beauty pageants, made for religious celebrations, or sold in tourist markets, traje is more than "mere cloth"—it plays an active role in the construction and expression of ethnicity, gender, education, politics, wealth, and nationality for Maya and non-Maya alike. Carol Hendrickson presents an ethnography of clothing focused on the traje—particularly women's traje—of Tecpán, Guatemala, a bi-ethnic community in the central highlands. She covers the period from 1980, when the recent round of violence began, to the early 1990s, when Maya revitalization efforts emerged. Using a symbolic analysis informed by political concerns, Hendrickson seeks to increase the value accorded to a subject like weaving, which is sometimes disparaged as "craft" or "women's work." She examines traje in three dimensions—as part of the enduring images of the "Indian," as an indicator of change in the human life cycle and cloth production, and as a medium for innovation and creative expression. From this study emerges a picture of highland life in which traje and the people who wear it are bound to tradition and place, yet are also actively changing and reflecting the wider world. The book will be important reading for all those interested in the contemporary Maya, the cultural analysis of material culture, and the role of women in culture preservation and change.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aCakchikel IndiansxClothing. 0aCakchikel IndiansxCostume. 0aCakchikel textile fabricszGuatemalazTecpán Guatemala. 0aCakchikel textile fabricszGuatemalazTecpán Guatemala. 0aCostumexSocial aspectszGuatemalazTecpán Guatemala. 0aCostumexSocial aspectszGuatemalazTecpán Guatemala. 0aCostumexSymbolic aspectszGuatemalazTecpán Guatemala. 0aCostumexSymbolic aspectszGuatemalazTecpán Guatemala. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/73099140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292799394423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292799394/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK